âœ… Step-by-Step: Encrypt and Store Artifactory Credentials

â¸»

1. Encrypt Your Artifactory Password or API Token

In your terminal (Git Bash / PowerShell / CMD):

mvn --encrypt-password

Youâ€™ll be prompted to enter your real password or token.
Maven returns something like:

{jSM1dfU2A3kfdLkjsdf==}

âœ… Copy this encrypted password. Do not store the plain text anywhere now.

â¸»

2. Update ~/.m2/settings-security.xml (optional)

This file contains the master key used for decryption.

Usually at:

C:\Users\<your-user>\.m2\settings-security.xml

If it doesnâ€™t exist, Maven creates one automatically with:

mvn --encrypt-password

You donâ€™t need to modify this file unless you want to re-use a specific master key (in teams, for example).

â¸»

3. Update settings.xml Securely

Edit your Maven settings file:
C:\Users\<your-user>\.m2\settings.xml

Add the Artifactory server section with the encrypted password:

<servers>
  <server>
    <id>artifactory-snapshot</id>
    <username>your-artifactory-username</username>
    <password>{jSM1dfU2A3kfdLkjsdf==}</password> <!-- ENCRYPTED -->
  </server>
</servers>

ğŸ”’ This is now safe to use, as the password is not in plaintext.

â¸»

âœ… Optional: Add Distribution Management in pom.xml

<distributionManagement>
  <snapshotRepository>
    <id>artifactory-snapshot</id>
    <url>https://artifactory.company.com/artifactory/libs-snapshot-local</url>
  </snapshotRepository>
</distributionManagement>


â¸»

4. Use mvn deploy as Usual

Now Maven will:
	â€¢	Use the encrypted password
	â€¢	Automatically decrypt it using your master key
	â€¢	Upload to Artifactory securely

â¸»

ğŸ§  Summary

Step	File	Secure?
Encrypt password	mvn --encrypt-password	âœ…
Store encrypted token	settings.xml	âœ…
Keep master key safe	settings-security.xml	âœ…
Avoid plain env vars or plaintext secrets	âœ…	âœ…


â¸»

ğŸ›¡ï¸ Extra Tip: Windows Credential Manager (Optional)

If you want to store the real token there and pull it dynamically into your Maven settings.xml, youâ€™ll need a custom Maven extension (not standard Maven behavior).

So the recommended approach remains:
	â€¢	Encrypt it using mvn --encrypt-password
	â€¢	Keep it in your settings.xml

